<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06178231 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06178231 </ACCESS><LEADPARA>  School officials would no longer have to tell girls how they can get legalabortions without their parents' consent under a bill approved by the MichiganLegislature. The House voted 90-15 in Lansing Tuesday to approve a bill endingthe requirement that schools tell students each September about a state lawthat allows girls 17 and younger to receive abortions without parental consentif a probate judge approves. The Senate already approved the measure, but musttake another vote for it to take effect immediately. Gov. John Engler, whoopposes abortion, is expected to sign it.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  MICHIGAN TO LIMIT SCHOOL ABORTION ADVICE  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  National News in Brief  </MEMO><BYLINE>  Mercury News Wire Services  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Home  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910626  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Wednesday  </DAY><MONTH>  June  </MONTH><PG.COL>  10A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  101  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Wednesday June 26, 199100178231,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>